I remember the first book and the first word that I read by myself (cat!!) because it was an exciting achievement, haha. Something about working hard to figure it out by myself made it feel like a magical discovery. Loved reading ever since! What were your favourite childhood books? Do you remember your first one or your most loved? I liked books of Russian fairy tales.
.
.
.
.

Maybe I just got more shy but it feels like there’s more social gymnastics in friendly conversations between adults. People being very cautious about showing their true selves, worrying about being judged, worrying about first impressions. All fair. But I miss the simpler time where you could get a new friend from playing make believe in the playground. .
Link to Patreon in bio! .
.

One of my earliest memories is dumping a quarter of a cup of water on my sister’s head because I couldn’t tell if the cup was empty (how?? I don’t know). It’s stupid but makes me laugh every time I remember it - kids are so ridiculous. My sis wasn’t even angry at me, just baffled.

One of my favourite memories is my Papa coming home from work and sneaking up on him as he took off his coat. He always pretended he couldn't see me even when I was being really obvious. He'd always lift me up above his head and I still remember how crazy it was seeing everything from that high and feeling like I could finally touch the ceiling.
.
.

That moment when you're having a moment of self-hatred and your loved ones refuse to let you insult yourself XD. I, like most people - don't have a symmetrical face and at times catch myself hating on the imperfections in the mirror. It's silly but low self-esteem doesn't go away overnight, so I'm fighting it one step at a time. And if you are like me, I am here to tell you - YOUR FACE IS CUTE AND I LOVE YOU.
.
.
.

I don't have any self control. This happens all the time and isn't limited to books. I've watched most of Stranger Things season 3 in a couple of nights and most of the Dark Crystal show in one night... With books it's happened with The Conjuring of Light, Fate of The Tearling, Wayward Son and most recently - Queen of Nothing. Like I said, no self control. You guys have any fun fantasy books to recommend me? I need to add to my to-read list.

A comic about my niece from when she was still a baby. I think babies climbing and falling from things or running into furniture is such a common occurrence that when you’re around them enough you just develop this instinct to try and catch them in a split second before even reacting. My sister caught me in a similar way when I was little and fell off a bunk bed (hm maybe there’s a comic in that haha).
